==English==
===Noun===
{{en-noun|sg=[[long]] [[shot]]}}

#{{idiom}}{{nautical}} Something [[unlikely]]; something that has little [[chance]] of happening or working. The term arose from the accuracy of early ship guns, which were effective only at close range and unlikely to hit the mark at any great distance.
#:''We can try your plan, but it's a '''long shot''' and it probably won't work.''
#{{cattag|Filmology}} A [[master]] shot, the primary wide [[shot]] of a [[scene]] into which the [[closeup]]s will be edited later.

====Synonyms====
*(''film''): [[establishing shot]], [[wide shot]]

